title: For Sale:  Scam Warning: The guy selling M1 Garands in Puyallup
postcontent:
The guy selling M1 Garands in Puyallup is buying and selling CMP M1 Garands at a huge markup. He has a "correct" M1 Garand for $1500 right now and claims it is a "vet bringback." If you look on the stock you can see a CMP Eagle stamp indicating it is not a bring back nor is it worth $1500. 

He states these are from his "personal collection" when in fact that is not true, he simply buys M1's from the CMP at a low cost and re sells them for much much more. They are not bring backs, and worth hundreds less than his selling price.


Save your money, do your research and buy your rifles from the Civilian Marksmanship Program for $550-$1000 ($1000 are premium rifles) don't let this guy scam you.

title: For Sale:  REAL DEAL British No.5 Mk I Jungle Carbine - Early Model, Made July 1944
location: Allendale - West of Grand Rapids, Grand Rapids, Michigan
postcontent:
Hello;

I have a genuine military British Jungle Carbine No.5 Mk I. Even the barrel with the forearm removed has the flutes cut into the barrel at the base of the receiver like it should be. With the high demand for real WWII military rifles, real (not converted SMLE's) No.5 Mk I Jungle Carbines are getting harder to find.

Only the bolt is not matching, every thing else matches including the magazine which many times does not. Bolt locks up tight. Correct 800 meter sight for a No.5 Mk I. Stock is in nice shape with usual dings, but nothing major and the rubber on the buttstock is good too. 

There is still cosmoline in the action. The person I got it from years ago said he got it from Century Arms in the late 1990's when they imported a bunch but never shot it, nor have I shot it as I left the cosmoline there until I was ready to use it, which I never did.

It was made in July pf 1944 in Fazakerley, England according to the serial number. The left side of receiver electro-pencil markings from the factory are covered up by paint, however barely visible. This paint was typical of Century Arms imports as they tried to "beautify" military guns they imported by slapping on dark paint to darken bluing.

Any questions, please ask.

FTF in Allendale until July 8th, then will consider shipping CONUS with buyer paying shipping to FFL. 

Thanks.
